    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-11T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-11T23:00:00-05:00" n="651"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.61331/55: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-12T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 12, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received September 12—7
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>443. Department’s telegram No. 216, September 9, 6 p.m., has been transmitted to
                    Shanghai with the request to follow the matter closely. Instructions have been
                    sent to Nanking by the Embassy’s September 12, noon as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Shanghai has been instructed to follow the matter closely. Please
                            approach those officials of the Ministry of Finance who would presumably
                                <pb facs="0711" n="616" xml:id="pg_616"/> be informed of the project
                            with a request for authoritative information regarding the matter. In
                            conferring with Chinese officials in this connection, the instructions
                            contained in the Department’s telegram No. 124, May 22, 6 p.m., should
                            be borne in mind. You should make an initial oral protest at the Foreign
                            Office if it seems that various current reports of a monopoly project
                            are essentially correct. Please keep the Department, Embassy and
                            Shanghai currently informed of developments.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The Embassy is studying the problem and will make formal protest should Nanking’s
                    information warrant such action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
